review_blob:
Tap @ Warpigs. Pours a hazy orange colour with a white head. Taste is intensely fruity with an abundance of tropical(-ish) fruits and hops. The. Hoppiness is almost drowned out by sweetness though. Pretty full body for such a low-ABV beer. Easily drinkable and not bad but nothing special either. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Bottle. Pours orange with a white head. Taste of wheat, malt, fruits, yeast, hops and spices. Sweet with a bitter hop-kick and a slightly tart finish. Crisp and easily drinkable.

Tap @ Brewdog Soho. Pours orange-y with a small white head. Fruity aroma of hops. Taste is of malts, lots of lighter fruits like peach and hoppy citrus notes. Medium body and carbonation. Nice bitter finish. Very quenchable. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Tap @ Brewdog Soho. Pours black with a beige head. Aroma of coffee and chocolate. The taste is nice and roasted and with flavours of roasted malts, coffee, dark bitter chocolate, hops and a bit of licorice. Very full body for a 7.5% beer. Soft carbonation. VERY tasty. :-)

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Tap @ Mother Kelly's. Pours dark brown with an off-white head. Roasty aroma. Taste is of caramel, chocolate, a bit of licorice and citrusy hops. Medium body and soft carbonation. Easily drinkable with a roasty and bitter finish. Delicious. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Cask. Light clear amber with a white head. Piney aroma. Taste of malt, caramel, fruits - especially citrus and piney hops (not many though). Medium body and flat carbonation. Refreshing with a bitter finish.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Keg @ Brewdog Clerkenwell. Black, off-white head with good lacing. Roasty aroma. Taste is of the usual suspects, coffee, licorice, some hops and chocolate. The flavours really comes out when it warms up a bit. Body is above average - I does feel 8.5%-ish. Nice bitter and roasted finish. I won't remember having this for long, but it's pretty good in the here and now. Just not something too special. But definitely above average. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle. Pours a beautiful clear pink-ish colour with a medium-sized white head. Taste is of malt, caramel, citrus fruits, spices and hops. Medium body and above average carbonation. Crisp and dry with a bitter hoppy finish. Boring and ordinary but pretty okay all things considered.

Bottle @home. Pours a hazy red colour with an off-white head. Aroma of malt, berries, caramel and sugars. Flavours are pretty much like the aroma indicates but has hops in it too. Taste is sweet and the mouthfeel is crisp and fresh. The finish is pretty caramel-y. Its not bad - Id go as far to say tasty...but while "solid" its really nothing special, so not one Ill buy again.
beer_name: Vestfyen Willemoes 55 Grader Nord Rd Lager

review_blob: Bottle @ home. Pours brown-ish with a beige head. Aroma is sweet. Taste is of malts - with the rye coming in loud and clear, dark fruits, sugars and a bit of hops. Body and carbonation is above medium. Roasty finish. Very good, as always with De Struise.
beer_name: Struise XXX Rye Quad Reserva (Bourbon Barrel Aged)

review_blob:
Tap @ ens lbar. Pours reddish, small white head. Not much aroma. Full malty body with LOTS of hops. Super fresh. Great!

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Can @ Brewdog Brussels. Black with no head. Great taste of roasted malts, coffee, some hops and warming alcohol. My cold probably robs me from the finer details but it's complex and delicious. It lacks body - it's too thin for a 12.7% beer but that being said it's very fresh and tasty. Would happily drink again. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: BrewDog Black Eyed King Imp Vietnamese Coffee Edition (Can)

review_blob: Bottle @ Brewdog Brussels. Black. No head. Lots of roasted malts, oak and alcohol. Complex and full. Lovely.
UPDATED: FEB 3, 2016

Bottle. Pours a clear golden colour with a huuuuge white head. Well, clear-ish - theres a lot of yeast floating arond in it. Aroma of malt, yeast and sugar. Taste is of malt, yeast, lots of hops, citrus, spices and alcohol. Above medium body and carbonation off the scale. Bitter and dry finish. Very good.

Can. Pours a clear copper colour with a one-finger fine white head. No aroma to speak of. Taste is of malt, sugar, hay, berries and boredom. Medium body and carbonation. Overly sweet with a slightly tart and hoppy finish. Shit beer. Once again Harboe proves that theyre terrible brewers.

On tap. Pours deep red, almost black with a beige head. Malt, roastiness, berries, spices and disappointment. Medium body and practically no carbonation. Seriously - it's an IPA...put some hops into it for crying out loud. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Brew By Numbers 15/04 Black IPA - Enigma

review_blob: Bottle(s) @ t Brugs Beertje & at home (bottled June 2014). Pours a hazy amber with a two-finger fine bubbly head. Aroma of malt, caramel, yeast, citrus and hops. Taste is of malt, yeast, caramel, bread, citrus fruits and spices. Above average body and average carbonation. Sweet with a slightly bitter finish with some alcohol in it. Perhaps a teeny tiny bit of tartness but definitely less than in Stille Nacht. Pretty good and very drinkable. I hope they still have them when I get back to t Brugs Beertje in a couple of weeks.

Bottle at home. Pours a hazy orange with a two-finger bubbly head. Aroma of hops, yeast and sugar. Taste is of malt, yeast, hops, caramel and lighter fruits with citrus notes. Medium body and lively carbonation. Not much alcohol in taste. Very fresh and drinkable.

Bottle at home. Pours completely black with a huge tan head. Aroma of roasted malt and fruit. Taste is of roasted malts, fruits, lots of hops, spices, coffee, licorice and sugar and yeast. Medium to full body and high carbonation. Bitter and burned with a nice roasted finish that has that De Dolle tartness to it. Pretty damn good.

Bottle at home. Pours cherry-red with a large off-white head. Aroma of fruits, spices, hops and nuts. Taste is pretty much like the aroma but also with flavours of caramel and molasses. Full body and very active carbonation. Bitter and fruity finish. Awesome. Ive had this one many times - even at the brewery and it never dissapoints. Love it.

75cl. bottle at home (and at a bar a couple of days ago). Pours a deep red colour with a large foamy off-white head. Aroma of fruit and spices. Taste is of malt, caramel, spices and lots of fruity flavours. Full body and lively and high carbonation. Long caramel and fruit finish along with alcohol. Pretty good and sweet...but for some reason not as sweet as the one I had a bar a couple of days ago. Perhaps brewed different years.

Bottle. Pours jet black with a medium sized foamy beige head. Aroma of roasted malts, fruits, rye and bourbon. Taste is of roasted malts - including lots of rye, hops, fruits, chocolate, licorice, vanilla, wood and bourbon. Full body and medium carbonation. Finish has lots of roasted malt, rye and some warming alcohol. Pretty damn good IS.
beer_name: Two Roads Igors Dream - Rye Whiskey Barrel Aged

review_blob:
Bottle. Pours black with an off-white head. Faint aroma of chocolate but not much else. Taste is of roasted malts but mostly just acidic. Coffee in the finish. Hoppy bitterness too. But overall very sour...ish. Definitely NOT a dry stout. In all fairness the bottle had passed its 'best before date' six months before being opened...but it does seem odd that this little time should make this much of a difference. It's probably just a pretty bad example of an 'American Dry Stout'. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle. Pours a deep red colour with a small off-white head. Faint fruity aroma. Taste is of malt, caramel, darker fruits & berries, sugar and spices - yknow - everything nice. Sweet with a lightly bitter finish. Very Christmassy and quite Belgian in style. So: not bad.

Bottle. Pours a hazy amber colour with a HUGE head. Seriously - give this beer an ID...its alive. BIG bubbly head and impossible to pour in one go, but the head dissappears into nothing in a minute. Lots of yeast sediment. Aroma of malt, fruits and spices. Taste is of malts, caramel, lots of fruits and spicy as hell. Bitter finish. Super complex but a bit too boozy mouthfeel. A bit unbalanced but tastes rather well.

Bottle. Pours a hazy red colour with a one-finger bubbly beige head. Aroma of fruits and Coca Cola. Taste is of malt, caramel, fruits and spices. Sweet with a bitter finish. Something about this one is not my cup of tea (so to speak).

Bottle. Pours a clear yellow colour with a short lived white head. Aroma is a bit fruity and spicy. Taste is of malt, spices, fruits and something I cant place. Bitter finish. Its not bad but you can do so much better. I wont have it again.

Tap. Pours black with a small off-white head. No aroma to speak of. Taste is of roasted malts, hops, a bit of dark fruits and a bit of chocolate. Toasty and bitter finish. By no means bad but just plain boring and generic. The only real positive thing is the bitterness which elevates it to slightly more drinkable than a Guinness. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle. Pours a murky brown colour with absolutely no head. Im not sure if I got a load of yeast in my glass or if its this colour naturally...but it looks disgusting and wrong. Aroma of malt and chocolate. Taste is of malt, coffee, hops, fruits and LOTS of chocolate. Full body and high carbonation. Bitter finish. Well, it looks terrible but luckily it tastes better than it looks. Its not too bad actually...perhaps it just looks that way. Just like Jessica Rabbit. But unlike this - with Jessica Rabbit I would go back for seconds. :-)

Bottle. Pours a clear golden colour with a one-finger white head. Faint sweet aroma. Taste of malt, fruits, spices, bread and citrussy flavours. A bitter finish. Not bad and reasonably drinkable. Luckily nowhere as undrinkable as their other New Nordic beer "Faddersbl".

Bottle. Pours a clear pale yellow colour with a huge white head. Hoppy and malty aroma. Taste is of malt, lots of hops and citrus flavours, yeast, spices and light citric fruits. Perfectly balanced carbonation and bitterness. Very tasty and very very good.

Bottle. Pours orange with a one-finger bubbly white head. Aroma of fruits and hops. Lots of citrus and hoppy floral notes in the taste that also have flavours of malt, yeast, fruits, bread and spices. Medium body and highly carbonated. Bitter and slightly tart finish. At first I liked it but by the end of the bottle I was happy it was nearly gone. Its okay but nothing more.

On tap @ Taphouse. Pours pitch black with a beige head. Aroma of roasted malts and hops. Taste is overflowing with hard roasted malts and an excessive amount of hops. Also has flavours of caramel, coffee, chocolate and licorice. Full-ish body and medium carbonation. The finish is bitter and really long and roasted. This is really good - just my kind of beer. If I had the equipment to pour kegged beer at home I'd definitely want a keg of this to drink at home. :-)

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle. Pours a hazy amber colour with a small off-white head. Aroma of sweet malts and hops. Taste is of malt, citrus and tropical fruits, yeast and a massive amount of hops. Juicy with a bitter finish. A bit boozy. Im glad I (randomly) chose to drink this as the last of my Polish beers. Surprisingly good.

50 cl. bottle. Pours a clear pale yellow with a white bubbly head. Very faint aroma of malt. Taste is of malt, hops and fruity flavours. Lots of carbonation. Dry with a bitter finish. Very drinkable...for a boring Pilsener.

Bottle. Pours a beautiful red color with an off-white dense head. Aroma of malt, caramel and fruits. Taste is of malt, caramel, roastiness, yeast, spices and hops. Sweet with a bitter finish. Not bad.

Bottle. Pours a reddish amber with a small white head. Sweet malt aroma. Taste is of malt, caramel, butter and hops. Sweet with a bitter finish. Not terribly bitter but the bitterness does linger for a while. Taste is good though...if a bit bland.

Bottle. Purs an unclear copper colour with a large white head. Lots of yeast floating around in this one. Aroma of malt and fruits. Taste is of malt, citrus fruits, caramel and lots of hops. Nice and bitter.

Bottle. Unclear red colour with a small white head. Aroma of malt and fruits. Taste is of malt, berries and spices. Smoky flavours too. Bitter. Terrible - drinking it now and considering pouring the rest in the drain.

Bottle. Pours a ruby red colour with a huge bubbly off-white head. Fruity aroma. Oh, and now I have foam on my nose. Taste is of malts, caramel, fruits, chocolate, sugar, spices and alcohol. Full body and average carbonation. Sweet with a bitter finish. Pretty ordinary. Solid and good...but ordinary.

Bottle. Pours almost black with some red in it and a big light-brown head. Aroma of roasted malt. Taste is of roasted malts, coffee, hops and licorice. Quite bitter - in taste and finish. Above average body and below average carbonation. It absolutely has that special Guinness taste but its not quite as good as the Special Export (Belgian version).

Bottle at home (and only a few weeks old). Pours a beautiful clear copper colour with a little to no (white) head. Fruity aroma of flowery citrusy hops. Taste is malty and super fruity, with notes of caramel, pine and lots of citrus fruits. Long bitter and fruity finish. Indeed a juicy and tasty mouthful.

Bottle. Pours a deep red colour with a bubbly off-white head. Aroma of malt, spices and yeast. Taste is of malt, honey, yeast, fruits and caramel. Medium body and high carbonation. Quite sweet. Not bad but the honey makes it less...good.

Bottle. Pours a deep red with a one-finger off-white head. Aroma of malt, fruits, spices and alcohol. Taste is of malt, caramel, fruits, sugars, spices and bitter hops. Full body and soft carbonation. Sweet with a bitter finish. Pretty good.
beer_name: Gordon Finest Scotch / Mc Douglas Scotch Ale

review_blob: Bottle. Pours an unclear golden colour with a huge white bubbly head. Aroma is malty and hoppy. Taste is of malt, lots of hops, citric fruits and yeast. Medium body and above average carbonation. Bitter finish. Pretty good.

Bottle @ home. Pours a reddish amber with a large bubbly off-white head. Aroma of malt, sugar, spices and nuts. Taste is like the aroma, but also with caramel, fruits and yeast. Sweet with a sugary and boozy finish. Very tasty and drinkable. Really good.

Bottle @ home. Pours a pale golden colour with a large white fluffy head. Aroma of malt, hay, yeast and spices. Taste is of malt, bread, yeast, hops, spices, light fruity flavours and sugars. Very Belgian. Initially sweet but has a bitter overall taste and finish. Full body and a slightly harsh carbonation and a boozy finish. Well balanced. Pretty good.

On tap at brewpub. Completely black with a small beige head. Aroma of malt and coffee. Taste of lightly roasted malts, chocolate, coffee, hops and licorice. Sweet with a bitter finish. Good aftertaste. A bit watery though. But pretty decent. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Nrrebro The Prince of Darkness is a Gentleman

review_blob:
On tap. Pours a hazy amber with a small white head. Hoppy aroma. Taste is if malt, lots and lots and lots of hops, resin and citrus. A bit sweet but it is completely dominated by hops. Bitter and dry. Very good. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Moylans Hopsickle Imperial India Pale Ale
